== History ==
According to tradition, the shrine was established in 852 (Ninju 2) as a branch of {{ill|Usa Jingū|ja|宇佐神宮|12=draft}}. It is said that in 824 (Tenchō 1), a divine oracle was received by a resident of Usa, leading to the shrine's founding. 

During the late 16th century, the shrine suffered attacks during the rule of Christian daimyō {{ill|Ōtomo Sōrin|ja|大友宗麟|12=draft}}, but it was restored in the early 17th century by {{ill|Takenaka Shigetoshi|ja|竹中重利|12=draft}}. It became the principal shrine of Takada and received patronage from successive feudal lords.

In the Meiji era, it was designated as a Prefectural Shrine, and in 1955, it was relocated approximately 80 meters east due to river reconstruction.

== Festivals ==
=== Autumn Grand Festival ===
The Autumn Grand Festival is held to express gratitude for the harvest. It includes the famous {{ill|River Crossing Ceremony|ja|川渡し神事|12=draft}}, also known as the Naked Festival. This ceremony, first recorded in 1084 (Eihō 4), features shrine bearers crossing the Katsura River with the {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿|12=draft}}. It is considered one of Japan's three major naked festivals, alongside the events at {{ill|Saidaiji Temple|ja|西大寺|12=draft}} in Okayama and {{ill|Hōfu Tenmangū|ja|防府天満宮|12=draft}} in Yamaguchi.

During the procession, the mikoshi is carried by groups alternating between land bearers and river bearers. The latter wade through the Katsura River wearing white loincloths and chanting loudly. A large ceremonial torch, measuring 16 meters and weighing 5 tons, is also prominently displayed.

<gallery>
File:Wakamiya Hachiman Naked Festival.jpg| River Crossing Ceremony at the Autumn Grand Festival
</gallery>

=== Horan Enya ===
{{Main|Horan Enya (Ōita)}}
This ceremonial boat procession was initiated in the Edo period to pray for safe sea transport. It is now held annually in early January.

== Architecture ==
The current main hall, constructed in 1833 (Tenpō 4), features a three-bay {{ill|nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|12=draft}} design with a cypress bark roof.

== Grounds ==
The shrine grounds house several auxiliary shrines, including:
* {{ill|Awashima Shrine|ja|粟嶋社|12=draft}}
* Miyajidake Shrine
* Inari Shrine
* Kotohira Shrine
* Gion Shrine

A stone arched bridge, constructed in 1860 (Man'en 1), spans a stream near the shrine gate. It is a meticulously crafted structure designated as an Ōita Prefectural Cultural Property.

== Cultural Properties ==
<small>Dates in parentheses indicate designation dates.</small>
; Ōita Prefectural Designation
* Stone Bridge (Tangible Cultural Property, 1983)
* Main Hall, Worship Hall, Karamon Gate, and Western Gate (Tangible Cultural Property, 2017)<ref>[http://www.oita-press.co.jp/1010000000/2017/02/22/JD0055491938 16th Century Medals and Other Cultural Properties Recognized in Ōita]</ref>
* Horan Enya (Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property, 1978)

== Access ==
* Train/Bus: Approximately 10 minutes by bus from {{ill|Usa Station|ja|宇佐駅|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Nippō Main Line|ja|日豊本線|12=draft}}.
* Car: About 30 minutes from {{ill|Usa-Beppu Road|ja|宇佐別府道路|12=draft}} Usa IC via Route 213.

== External Links ==
* [http://hadaka-matsuri.com/ Wakamiya Hachiman Autumn Grand Festival - Naked Festival] (Official Site)

