'''Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine''' (若宮八幡神社) is a {{ill|shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Bungotakada|ja|豊後高田市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ōita Prefecture. It holds the rank of a former {{ill|Prefectural shrine|ja|県社|12=draft|12=draft}} and is commonly referred to as "Wakamiya-sama" (若宮様).

The shrine is renowned for its two traditional festivals: the {{ill|Horan Enya (Ōita)|ja|ホーランエンヤ (大分県)|12=draft|12=draft}} held in early January, and the autumn festival's {{ill|River Crossing Ceremony|ja|川渡し神事|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as the Naked Festival) held in November. The site is also famed for its hydrangeas.

== Deities ==
The principal deity is '''Ōsazaki no Mikoto''' (Emperor Nintoku). The following deities are also enshrined:
* {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大御神|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Tamanooya-no-Mikoto|ja|玉祖命|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Hachiman|ja|品陀別命|1=Emperor Ōjin|lt=Hondawake no Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}} (Emperor Ōjin)
* {{ill|Hayasumi Wakatake Mikoto|ja|隼総別皇子|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Ōwae Mikoto|ja|大葉枝皇子|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Kowaeshi Mikoto|ja|小葉枝皇子|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Menotori no Miko|ja|雌鳥皇女|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Tagitsuhime|ja|多岐都比売命|1=Tagitsuhime|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Ichikishimahime|ja|市寸嶋比売命|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Takamimusubi|ja|高皇産霊尊|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Five Male and Three Female Deities|ja|五男三女神|12=draft|12=draft}}

== History ==
According to tradition, the shrine was established in 852 (Ninju 2) as a branch of {{ill|Usa Jingū|ja|宇佐神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is said that in 824 (Tenchō 1), a divine oracle was received by a resident of Usa, leading to the shrine's founding. 

During the late 16th century, the shrine suffered attacks during the rule of Christian daimyō {{ill|Ōtomo Sōrin|ja|大友宗麟|12=draft|12=draft}}, but it was restored in the early 17th century by {{ill|Takenaka Shigetoshi|ja|竹中重利|12=draft|12=draft}}. It became the principal shrine of Takada and received patronage from successive feudal lords.

In the Meiji era, it was designated as a Prefectural Shrine, and in 1955, it was relocated approximately 80 meters east due to river reconstruction.

== Festivals ==
=== Autumn Grand Festival ===
The Autumn Grand Festival is held to express gratitude for the harvest. It includes the famous {{ill|River Crossing Ceremony|ja|川渡し神事|12=draft|12=draft}}, also known as the Naked Festival. This ceremony, first recorded in 1084 (Eihō 4), features shrine bearers crossing the Katsura River with the {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is considered one of Japan's three major naked festivals, alongside the events at {{ill|Saidaiji Temple|ja|西大寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in Okayama and {{ill|Hōfu Tenmangū|ja|防府天満宮|12=draft|12=draft}} in Yamaguchi.

During the procession, the mikoshi is carried by groups alternating between land bearers and river bearers. The latter wade through the Katsura River wearing white loincloths and chanting loudly. A large ceremonial torch, measuring 16 meters and weighing 5 tons, is also prominently displayed.

<gallery>
File:Wakamiya Hachiman Naked Festival.jpg| River Crossing Ceremony at the Autumn Grand Festival
</gallery>

=== Horan Enya ===
{{Main|Horan Enya (Ōita)}}
This ceremonial boat procession was initiated in the Edo period to pray for safe sea transport. It is now held annually in early January.

== Architecture ==
The current main hall, constructed in 1833 (Tenpō 4), features a three-bay {{ill|nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|12=draft|12=draft}} design with a cypress bark roof.

== Grounds ==
The shrine grounds house several auxiliary shrines, including:
* {{ill|Awashima Shrine|ja|粟嶋社|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Miyajidake Shrine
* Inari Shrine
* Kotohira Shrine
* Gion Shrine

A stone arched bridge, constructed in 1860 (Man'en 1), spans a stream near the shrine gate. It is a meticulously crafted structure designated as an Ōita Prefectural Cultural Property.

